Hey, founder, Why are you feeling low today?    The million-dollar idea does not excite you anymore.    Simple things look like an uphill task. Motivation is at an all-time low:  We all face ups and downs in our start-up journey.    But why? From my real experience, I could think of possible reasons.    Funding: Running low on funds can really impact a business, especially for committed founders. Competition: Standing out in a competitive business landscape can lead to discouragement among startup founders.  Personal Sacrifices: Starting and growing a business often involves personal sacrifices, leading to stress and burnout.  Setbacks: Despite planning, setbacks are inevitable and can be demoralizing for founders.  Burnout: Demanding startup responsibilities can lead to burnout, affecting motivation and well-being.    What to do: Talk to people you connect with.   Your friends, family, or mentors. Do not be tough on yourself.  You have it in you.   Give yourself a little time.  It is a long-haul game.   Your mental well-being comes first.

"Startup Journey: From Idea to Launch in 5 Weeks"  Embark on an interactive, hands-on experience where you not only learn the ins and outs of launching a startup but actually put those learnings into action. This 5-week course is designed for budding entrepreneurs ready to turn their ideas into realities.  Format & Pricing:  Mode: Cohort, Live weekly calls (recorded for those who can't attend). Duration: 5 weeks. Group Size: Limited to 6-8 participants for personalized attention. Investment: $150 - $200 total. Course Breakdown:  Call 1: "Laying the Foundation" Dive into the methodology behind your startup process (literally your twitter thread). Explore the process of ideation and brainstorming. Assignment: Everyone submit their  startup idea on a platform you develop / host (or just google docs).  Call 2: "Pitch Perfect" Participants pitch their startup ideas (60-second limit) and receive real-time feedback and insights from you and participants. Then you teach them to set goals for the coming week, alongside with your own process. Keep objectives achievable.  Call 3: "Gaining Traction" from now it's a peer-group for accountability and support. Showcase the deliverables of your startup, and ask them to show theirs. Call 4: "Maintaining Momentum"Continue with the interactive show-and-tell sessions. Engage in peer group feedback, delve deeper into each startup's journey, and overcome challenges together.  Call 5: "Ready, Set, Launch!"Finalize strategies, business models, and marketing plans. Celebrate the progress of each startup. Discuss next steps and post-course support.
